  "text": "The Arrhenius plot of the process is shown in Figure 7 . A plot of ln(k) versus (1/T) presents a linear relationship, where the slope is (−Ea/R), and the intercept is lnA. According to the slope (−Ea/R), the activation energy (Ea) was calculated to be 51.7 kJ/mol. Generally, chemically-controlled processes are strongly dependent on temperature, and the activation energy is usually in the range of 40-100 kJ/mol, while the diffusion controlled processes are slightly dependent on the temperature, with the activation energy usually less than 21 kJ/mol −1 [CITATION_1] , which further proved that in this process, the chemical reaction is the rate-limiting step. In order to determine the reaction order, the results on the effect of the sawdust/ore mass ratio and the sulfuric acid concentration were applied to the chemical reaction kinetic model, as shown in Figures 8 and 9 . According to the slopes of the straight lines, the values of rate constant kr were determined, and a good linear relationship was presented. The plots of ln(k) versus ln(H2SO4) and ln(sawdust/ore) were constructed to determine the respective reaction orders. The results shown in Figures 8 and 9 indicate a reaction order of 0.57 with respect to the sawdust/ore mass ratio and a reaction order of 1.66 with respect to the H2SO4 concentration. In order to determine the reaction order, the results on the effect of the sawdust/ore mass ratio and the sulfuric acid concentration were applied to the chemical reaction kinetic model, as shown in Figures 8 and 9 . According to the slopes of the straight lines, the values of rate constant k r were determined, and a good linear relationship was presented. The plots of ln(k) versus ln(H 2 SO 4 ) and ln(sawdust/ore) were constructed to determine the respective reaction orders. The results shown in Figures 8 and 9 indicate a reaction order of 0.57 with respect to the sawdust/ore mass ratio and a reaction order of 1.66 with respect to the H 2 SO 4 concentratio